    <item>
      <title>DBIx::Class::Async - Oracle Database</title>
      <link>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/dbix-async-oracle/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 01 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/dbix-async-oracle/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h4 id=&#34;disclaimer-image-is-generated-using-chatgpt&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DISCLAIMER:&lt;/strong&gt; Image is generated using &lt;code&gt;ChatGPT&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It has been a long time since I shared an update regarding &lt;code&gt;DBIx::Class::Async&lt;/code&gt;. The reason is simple: no known critical issues have been reported. While &lt;code&gt;DBIx::Class::Async v0.65&lt;/code&gt; is officially still &lt;code&gt;experimental&lt;/code&gt;, it is quite &lt;code&gt;stable&lt;/code&gt;. I am not in a rush to declare it &lt;code&gt;production ready&lt;/code&gt; just yet.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;However, yesterday, I received an email regarding the project&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/images/blog/email-notice.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Email Notice&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;To be honest, as of &lt;code&gt;v0.65&lt;/code&gt;, I haven&amp;rsquo;t done any testing against an &lt;code&gt;Oracle&lt;/code&gt; database. I wasn&amp;rsquo;t entirely sure how to reply to the email, but my first thought was to add basic tests for &lt;code&gt;Oracle&lt;/code&gt; database interaction.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>DBIx::Class - Schema Class</title>
      <link>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/dbic-schema/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 30 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/dbic-schema/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h4 id=&#34;disclaimer-image-is-generated-using-chatgpt&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DISCLAIMER:&lt;/strong&gt; Image is generated using &lt;code&gt;ChatGPT&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In my &lt;a href=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/dbic-resultset&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;earlier post&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, I discussed about &lt;code&gt;Result&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;ResultSet&lt;/code&gt; class. In this post I am focussing on the &lt;code&gt;Schema&lt;/code&gt; class. I know, this feels a bit backward!&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;While working on my first book &lt;a href=&#34;https://perlschool.com/books/design-patterns&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Design Patterns in Modern Perl&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, I learned that nothing is truly &lt;code&gt;&amp;quot;complete&amp;quot;&lt;/code&gt; until it is published. Even then, there always seem to be a few things left pending. As I progress through the manuscript for my current book on &lt;code&gt;DBIx::Class&lt;/code&gt;, I&amp;rsquo;ve realised that something very important was missing.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
